Since 25 March, all international flights to and from Kenya have been suspended by the Kenyan government, with the exception of specially negotiated repatriation flights and cargo flights. Crew must observe strict guidelines. This suspension was extended on 6 June for a further 30 days.
Commercial repatriation flight to the UK on 25 June
Following discussions between the British High Commission, the Government of Kenya and international airlines, Kenya Airways plan to operate a direct commercial repatriation flight from Nairobi’s Jomo Kenyatta International Airport to London Heathrow on 25 June at 9.20am (local time), subject to demand.
How to book
To secure your seat on this flight, you can book tickets on the Kenya Airways flight details will be displayed from 16 June or call the Kenya Airways call centre now on +254 711 024 747.
You will need to pay for your return travel to the UK. If you cannot afford the travel costs and have exhausted all other options for getting funds, you may be eligible to apply for an emergency loan from the government. This is a last resort option and you would need to repay the loan when you are back in the UK. For more information, contact the British High Commission at Nairobi.ConsularEscalations@fco.gov.uk.
Commercial repatriation flight to the UK on 18 June
The Kenya Airways direct commercial repatriation flight from Nairobi’s Jomo Kenyatta International Airport to London Heathrow on 18 June is now fully booked.
Medical certificate requirements
The Government of Kenya and Kenya Airways require passengers and crew on Kenya Airways repatriation flights to produce a medical certificate confirming they are free of COVID-19. The cost of a COVID-19 test will not be included in the ticket price.
Once you have paid for your flight, you should book a test at the Nairobi Hospital or any Lancet Laboratories branch, where you will need to pay for your test. Results should take 24 hours and will be shared with you and Kenya Airways. Test results must be from within 72 hours of check-in.
If you test positive you will not be allowed to travel and will receive a refund of the airfare. You must follow Ministry of Health instructions.
Your journey home: re-entering the UK
When you return, you must follow the rules for entering the UK. You:
need to provide your journey and contact details up to 48 hours before you’re due to arrive in the UK
are not allowed to leave the place you’re staying for the first 14 days you’re in the UK except in very limited situations (known as ‘self-isolating’)
See also the list of people who are exempt from the border rules.
The National Travel Health Network and Centre (NaTHNaC) also provides advice on how to stay safe as you travel by air.
Future travel options
The British High Commission continues to work with the government of Kenya and international airlines to determine further options for helping British nationals who wish to return home. However, you should not expect any additional flights immediately.
If you’re in Kenya and wish to register your intention to leave, email the following details for you and any family members travelling with you to returnfromKenya@fco.gov.uk:
your full name as shown on your passport
passport number
date of birth
place of residence in UK
where exactly you are currently staying in Kenya
email address and telephone number (check that you are able to receive phone calls from unidentified numbers, including internationally, in case we need to reach you)
any specific medical needs/vulnerabilities
If registered with the British High Commission, we will alert you to any further opportunities to book onto flights departing Kenya for the UK, should these become available. This travel advice will also be updated when future options become available.
You will need to pay for your return travel to the UK. If you cannot afford the travel costs and have exhausted all other options for getting funds, you may be eligible to apply for an emergency loan from the government. This is a last resort option and you would need to repay the loan when you are back in the UK. For more information, contact the British High Commission via webform.
If you cannot leave Kenya at this time, see advice on staying in Kenya during coronavirus.
Help and support
If you’re in Kenya and in need of urgent help, contact the British High Commission.
If you are vulnerable with health issues, an older person, or will be travelling with young children, you can call: +254202844000 or +254 20 287 3000 and follow the options for consular assistance. The numbers are available 24/7.
The High Commission cannot provide further information or advice about departure options over the phone. This page will be updated when departure options become available or, if you are registered with the High Commission, we will alert you. To get the latest information sign up for travel advice email alerts.
